  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "marty-cagan",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Ready as reviewer, product assessment of all 5 tasks",
    "content": "Marty Cagan here, ready as Reviewer. I've read my profile, PROJECT.md, and TEAM_AGREEMENTS.md. I've reviewed the task list and the current codebase structure.\n\nProduct assessment of current tasks:\n\n**Task #1 (Lea driving - password toggle hidden input)**: This is a legitimate bug fix. The registration form breaks when JS toggle is active because the confirm field gets removed from the DOM. Users who enable the password visibility toggle would get a 422 error -- that's a broken registration flow. Must fix. Appropriate scope.\n\n**Task #2 (Lea driving - CSS gaps)**: These are visual polish items Steve Schoger identified. They affect perceived quality -- empty error containers taking up space, unstyled cancel links, unstyled logout button. Small but they matter for the \"fast, simple\" experience we defined in our success criteria.\n\n**Tasks #3-5 (Carson driving - HTMX focus management, empty state, inline editing)**: These are progressive enhancement items. #3 and #4 are accessibility/usability fixes -- after deleting a todo via HTMX, focus gets lost and the empty state doesn't reappear. These directly affect the \"accessible\" success criterion. #5 (inline editing) is a \"should have\" enhancement from US-8 that improves the editing workflow. All appropriate scope for polish.\n\nAll five tasks fit within MVP polish -- no scope creep. I'm ready to review each change for product fit as the drivers complete their work."
  }
}
